A few more extra things about managing jobs

Suppose your job number is 340347 (which you learn after running squeue --me)

  • How to cancel your jobs
    • If you realize you ran a job thats already run a second time by accident
    • If you realize that after you started a job, theres a typo that will kill your job in the future
scancel 340347
  • How to check how much memory your job took
sacct -j 340347 --format=JobID,JobName,MaxRSS,MaxRSSNode%15

  • In this screenshot, we can see that our job took 112K (i.e., 112 Kilobytes, or 0.1 Megabytes) to complete.

Therefore, the usual workflow is this:

  • When you are running a job on Bayes, a good initial estimate of how much memory you need to request (the 10gb in #SBATCH --mem-per-cpu=10gb in your .slurm script) is: the size of your largest dataset your script analyzes multiplied by 5. (R is not very effecient with its memory.) If you are ever unsure, 10gb is always a safe place to start.
    • This number should be larger than what you really need (since your job will get terminated prematurely if it actually needs more memory than you request), but not too execessively large (or else youll be griefing someone else who wants to use the server)
  • Then, after your job runs and completes, use the above sacct -j [[JOB-ID]] --format=JobID,JobName,MaxRSS,MaxRSSNode%15 line to see how much memory your job actually used.
  • Based on this, adjust your #SBATCH --mem-per-cpu=10gb to be more accurate. Usually, you want to pad the amount of memory your job actually used by 10%-25% (just to be on the safe side).

PkgDown

Its honestly much easier than you might realize. All the steps you need is at https://pkgdown.r-lib.org/articles/pkgdown.html.

You need the usethis and pkgdown packages, and all you need to do is run the following lines to get a local (i.e., on your laptop) working version of your package.

# Make sure your package is all set to go first
devtools::check()

# Run once to configure package to use pkgdown
usethis::use_pkgdown()
# After running this, a file called "_pkgdown.yml" might open.
# You can save and close it.

# Run to build the website
pkgdown::build_site()
# The local version of your website might open up.

A few notes

  • pkgdown will try to literally rebuild all your vignettes specifically the .Rmd files under the vignettes folder. So please make sure your vignettes can be compiled and do not load any local files (.RData, .rds, .csv, etc.).
  • Before you go onto the next step, if your R package is associated with a GitHub page, things might go smoother if your GitHub repository is set to Public.

Pushing your website to GitHub to have a PkgDown website

Lets say youre happy with the local-version of your PkgDown website. Then, to have the PkgDown website online,

  • First, make sure your R package is the only thing for a Git repository, and that the Git repository is on GitHub. (Essentially, make sure you can view your package on GitHub.com.)
  • Then, run the following line.
usethis::use_pkgdown_github_pages()
  • You might get a prompt that asks you if you want to overwrite _pkgdown.yml. Say yes.

  • Then, a whole bunch of things will start happening

  • Then, push your new Git repository from your laptop onto GitHub. (There will be a lot of new files. Just push it all.)

  • On GitHub.com, you should now see a curious circle next to your commit message. (If you pushed your package just a minute ago, this will be an orange circle that says pending. If its been a few minutes and nothing bad happened, itll be a green checkmark that says success. If you see a red circle/cross, it means you have an error in your R package setup you either messed with the PkgDown files too much, or your R package didnt pass devtools::check() originally.)

  • If you click on the orange circle (pending) while its still there, you will be brought to the Actions page

  • This shows you that GitHub.com (i.e., servers run by GitHub) are currently recompiling your R package (importantly, re-running the vignettes) to build your website. This is why its important to be attentive that your vignettes have no errors and it doesnt require any local files.

  • Once you see a green checkmark next to your commit, youre all set to go!

  • If you didnt mess with the settings, if your username is linnykos and your packages name is UWBiost561, this means your PkgDown website is at https://linnykos.github.io/UWBiost561/.

  • Congratulations!

Some basic things you help your PkgDown website

You can refer to our courses example PkgDown website https://linnykos.github.io/561_s2025_example/ (and the corresponding GitHub repository, https://github.com/linnykos/561_s2025_example) to see some things to make your website easier to navigate or more useful

  • Create a README.md file. This goes next to DESCRIPTION file in your R package. This file could say some simple things:
    • Put the URL of both your GitHub repository (ex: https://github.com/linnykos/561_s2025_example) and your PkgDown website (ex: https://linnykos.github.io/561_s2025_example/). This is so people can easily navigate between both
    • Put the output of your devtools::session_info() so other users know exactly what your R setup was when you developed the package
  • Under the vignettes folder, create a new vignette that specifically is named after your package. For example, if your package is named UWBiost561, this vignette must be specifically named UWBiost561.Rmd. When you construct your Pkgdown website, this vignette will not go under Articles, but instead, under Get started.
    • Typically, this vignette contains instructions on how to install your package (for example, using devtools::install_github()) and how to run a simple demo.

After you make any changes, be sure to re-run devtools::check() (to make sure your package is still in good condition) and then pkgdown::build_site(). Once both these functions run smoothly and complete, you can push your changes to GitHub, let GitHub rebuild your website, and then youre good to go!

Setting up a GitHub Page (i.e., Github.io page)

Switching gears. Onto your personal website!

See https://docs.github.com/en/pages/quickstart. Follow the directions until the end of Creating your website.

  • Your website is its own (new) GitHub repository

  • To see how these websites were built, type in: https://github.com/[[github username]]/[[github username]].github.io.

  • For example, https://github.com/linnykos/linnykos.github.io

  • Pick a page whose layout you like, visit these Github.io pages.

  • If you like a layout, visit the repository itself to find all the files used the create the page.

  • Then, download all the files and put it in your repository, and start changing all the content to be your owns. (Be sure to give credit!)
